The paper deals with the maximum cardinality matching problem in random graphs, which is a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The algorithm proposed in the paper is a heuristic, which is a common approach in computer science for solving optimization problems, and thus the paper could also belong to the sub-category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the behavior of commonly used greedy matching heuristics, which is related to the field of graph theory (cs.GT). The experimental evidence presented in the paper involves analyzing the performance of the algorithm on random graphs, which could be considered a problem in numerical analysis (cs.NA). Finally, the paper proposes a new algorithm that is more reliable than existing heuristics, which could be relevant to the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI) where matching problems are often studied.
